  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhancing the resilience, health and prosperity of rural communities in Karukh district, Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">-Digging a bore well in depth of 100 m and standing metal water tanker in Anbar village. The water tanker will have the capacity to old 15,000 litres of water at any given time. A solar water pump (30 solar penals) will be installed &#x2013; with the capacity of filtering 75,000 litres of water a day - as well as 28 taps in five parts of the village to ensure that residents are able to easily access the water.  
-Constructing a spring, filter house and water reservoir at Seyah Chobak village. The filter house will have the capacity to filter 1500 litres of water and the reservoir will be able to hold 12,000 litres and total 32 taps will be standed in Seyah Chobak village as well  
-Establishment of Community Based Disaster Risk Management (CBDRM) committee and task force in both villages as well as running a seris of DRR, hygiene and sanitation practice and water resource management trainings, benefiting 660 coemmunity members in total. Hygiene toolkits will also be distributed to all participants.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is expected to bring significant long-term improvements to the basic needs of the villages. By helping them to secure a permanent source of clean water, it is expected that the targeted beneficiaries will enjoy improved health, improved livelihoods, increased economic productivity, greater food security and overall empowerment.</narrative>
  </description>
